# Method

## Participants

`r n_participants` participants completed the experiment, comprising `r n_l1` L1 Spanish speakers (IDs beginning with 1) and `r n_l2` L2 Spanish learners (IDs beginning with 2).

## Procedure

Participants completed a three-phase Spanish stress-suffix association task in PsychoPy. The pre-test consisted of 360 trials across 6 blocks, followed by a 120-trial training phase with feedback, and concluded with a 360-trial post-test (parallel structure to the pre-test). On each trial, participants heard a spoken stimulus and selected between *PRESENTE* and *PASADO* response options.

Pre- and post-test stimuli were drawn from six conditions, labeled by verb stress (paroxytone, oxytone), noun match (Match, Mismatch), and verb match (Match, Mismatch), with splice variants from two source nouns (Table 1). Six of the eight possible cells in the paroxytone/oxytone Ă— noun-match Ă— verb-match design were sampled; the noun-mismatch + verb-mismatch combinations were not included. Training stimuli comprised two conditions: `parox` (paroxytone present, condition a) and `oxy` (oxytone past, condition b).

## Analysis

Reaction time (RT) was analyzed three ways: (a) on correct trials only, (b) on incorrect trials only, and (c) on all trials regardless of accuracy. All RT measures used the same trimming criteria, excluding responses faster than 200 ms or slower than 5,000 ms. All analyses were run in R using the tidyverse. Group-level means were computed in two steps to avoid bias from unequal cell sizes: trial-level data were first averaged within participant, then averaged across participants.

